Project: Orange Minds Trivia App
Team: Oranges
Team Members: Anagha Roy, Ryan Richardson, Jasmeen Garcha

ADR 1 – Development Framework
Context
The Orange Minds application will be a trivia app designed to run on Android devices. 
The development framework must allow the team to build a mobile application efficiently while supporting interactive user interfaces and simple navigation between screens.
The team considered several frameworks including Ionic, Cordova, NativeScript, and React Native.

The framework must:
- Support Android development
- Be easy for the team to learn
- Allow fast user interface development
- Have strong documentation and community support

Decision
The team decided to use React Native as the development framework.

Reasoning
React Native allows developers to build mobile applications using JavaScript and reusable components. 
It has strong community support and extensive documentation, which makes it easier for the team to learn and implement.

Consequences
Using React Native allows the team to develop the application more efficiently while maintaining a responsive and modern user interface.
However, the team will need to learn React Native structure and component-based design during development.

ADR 2 – Navigation Strategy
Context
The Orange Minds trivia application will include several screens that allow users to navigate through different features of the app. 
These screens must be organized in a way that makes navigation simple and intuitive for users.

The application will include the following pages:
- Home Page
- Login Page
- Quiz Page
- Scores Page
- Profile Page
- Account Information Page
- Settings Page
- Information Page

Users must be able to easily access the main features of the application while maintaining a clear and logical flow between screens.

Decision
The team decided to implement Stack Navigation combined with Tab Navigation.
The Home Page will act as the main entry point to the application. From there, users will be able to navigate to the quiz, scores, and profile sections.
Tab navigation will allow quick access to the main areas of the application, while stack navigation will allow users to move forward and backward between related screens.

Reasoning
This navigation structure allows the application to remain organized while still providing quick access to important features. 
Users will be able to easily navigate between quiz gameplay, score tracking, and profile management.
Stack navigation is also useful for screens such as login and quiz progression where users move step-by-step through the app.

Consequences
The Orange Minds app will use a combination of tab and stack navigation to create a clear and user-friendly interface.

ADR 3 – Hardware Integration
Context
Mobile devices provide several hardware capabilities such as GPS, cameras, fingerprint scanners, speakers, and vibration motors.
The Orange Minds trivia application focuses on answering questions and receiving feedback. 
The team considered whether any hardware features could enhance the user experience without adding unnecessary complexity to the application.
One feature that could improve the user experience is vibration feedback when users answer questions.

Decision
The team decided to integrate device vibration feedback into the Orange Minds application.

Reasoning
Vibration feedback will provide immediate physical feedback when users answer a trivia question.

Examples include:

- A short vibration when an answer is correct
- A slightly longer vibration when an answer is incorrect

This feature improves the user experience by providing quick feedback without requiring additional visual elements. 
It also makes the app feel more interactive and responsive.
Vibration is supported by most Android devices and can be implemented easily using mobile device APIs.

Consequences
The application will use the Android vibration motor to provide feedback when users answer trivia questions. This enhances the user experience while keeping the implementation simple.

ADR 4 – Data Storage Strategy

Context
The trivia application needs to store trivia questions, categories, and player scores.
The team considered the following options:
- A remote database
- Local storage
- Encrypted local storage

A remote database would require internet connectivity and additional backend infrastructure, requiring hosting and will increase development complexity.

Decision
The team decided to use local storage.

Reasoning
Local storage allows the application to store trivia questions and player scores directly on the device. 
This allows the app to function without requiring an internet connection and simplifies development.
Since the data stored is not sensitive, encryption is not required.

Consequences
Using local storage allows the trivia app to run offline and simplifies the overall architecture.
However, trivia questions will need to be packaged with the application when it is built.